# 🛠️ Setup Guide — Inventory Management System

---

## ✅ Prerequisites

Make sure you have the following installed:

| Tool | Version | Download |
|---|---|---|
| Python | 3.10+ | https://python.org |
| Node.js | 18+ | https://nodejs.org |
| Docker | Latest | https://docker.com |
| Docker Compose | Latest | Included with Docker Desktop |
| Git | Latest | https://git-scm.com |

---

## 📥 1. Clone the Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-username/inventory-project.git
cd inventory-project
```

---

## 🔐 2. Configure Environment Variables

Create a `.env` file in the **root** of the project:

```bash
# On Linux/Mac
touch .env

# On Windows
type nul > .env
```

Add the following to `.env`:

```env
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://<user>:<password>@<host>/<dbname>?sslmode=require
BREVO_API_KEY=your_brevo_api_key_here
SENDER_EMAIL=your_sender@example.com
```

> ⚠️ **Important:** Never commit `.env` to GitHub. It is already listed in `.gitignore`.

---

## 🐳 Option A — Run with Docker (Recommended)

### Step 1: Build and start all services

```bash
docker-compose up --build
```

### Step 2: Access the app

| Service | URL |
|---|---|
| Frontend | http://localhost:5173 |
| Backend API | http://localhost:8000 |
| Swagger Docs | http://localhost:8000/docs |

### Step 3: Stop the services

```bash
docker-compose down
```

---

## 💻 Option B — Run Locally (Without Docker)

### Backend Setup

```bash
# Create and activate virtual environment
python -m venv venv

# On Linux/Mac
source venv/bin/activate

# On Windows
venv\Scripts\activate

# Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# Start the backend server
uvicorn main:app --reload --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000
```

Backend will be live at: **http://localhost:8000**

---

### Frontend Setup

Open a **new terminal** window:

```bash
cd frontend

# Install dependencies
npm install

# Start the dev server
npm run dev
```

Frontend will be live at: **http://localhost:5173**

---

## 🗄️ 3. Database Setup

This project uses **PostgreSQL via Neon** (serverless cloud DB). The tables are auto-created on first run using SQLAlchemy:

```python
models.Base.metadata.create_all(bind=engine)
```

No manual migration needed — just ensure your `DATABASE_URL` in `.env` is correct and the DB is accessible.

---

## 🧪 4. Test the API

Once the backend is running, open Swagger UI:

```
http://localhost:8000/docs
```

You can test all endpoints directly from the browser.

Or use `curl`:

```bash
# Create a product
curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/products \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"name": "Laptop", "sku": "LAP-001", "price": 999.99, "stock_quantity": 50}'

# List all products
curl http://localhost:8000/products

# Create a customer
curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/customers \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"name": "John Doe", "email": "john@example.com"}'

# Place an order
curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/orders \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"customer_id": 1, "product_id": 1, "quantity": 2}'
```

---

## 📧 5. Email Setup (Brevo)

1. Sign up at [https://www.brevo.com](https://www.brevo.com)
2. Go to **Settings → API Keys** and generate a key
3. Add it to `.env` as `BREVO_API_KEY`
4. Set `SENDER_EMAIL` to a verified sender address in your Brevo account

> Email sending is optional — if the keys are missing, orders still work and the email step is silently skipped.

